Help me to debug the attached sql snippet which gives the following error:

Failed to run sql query: ERROR: 42P07: relation "tenants" already exists

Understanding the error

The Postgres error 42P07: relation "tenants" already exists means your SQL tried to create a table (or view/index/sequence) named tenants that already exists in the database.

Common causes:

  • Running CREATE TABLE tenants without IF NOT EXISTS
  • Creating a table in the same schema with the same name during repeated migrations
  • A prior object named tenants exists but in a different type (e.g., a view or materialized view)
  • Youre connected to a different schema than expected (search_path ambiguity)

How to fix

Choose one of these approaches depending on intent:

  1. Make creation idempotent (recommended for migrations)
  • Add IF NOT EXISTS to your CREATE statements. Example:

SQL Query 

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS public.tenants (
  id uuid PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
  name text NOT NULL,
  created_at timestamptz NOT NULL DEFAULT now()
);
  • If you also create indexes/constraints, guard them too:

SQL Query 

CREATE UNIQUE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS tenants_name_key ON public.tenants (name);
  1. Drop before create (destructive; confirm first) Only if you intend to replace the table. This will remove data.

SQL Query 

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS public.tenants CASCADE;
CREATE TABLE public.tenants ( ... );
  1. Convert to ALTER if the table already exists If youre trying to add columns/constraints to an existing table, use ALTER TABLE:

SQL Query 

ALTER TABLE public.tenants
  ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS plan text,
  ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS is_active boolean NOT NULL DEFAULT true;
  1. Ensure the correct schema is referenced
  • Always schema-qualify: public.tenants (or your custom schema).
  • If you have a different object type with the same name, drop/rename the old object or choose a new name:

SQL Query 

-- Example: replace a view named tenants
DROP VIEW IF EXISTS public.tenants;

Quick diagnosis queries

If you can share the snippet, I can tailor the exact fix. Meanwhile, here are read-only checks you can run to see what exists:

  • What object is tenants?

SQL Query 

SELECT n.nspname AS schema, c.relkind AS kind, c.relname AS name
FROM pg_class c
JOIN pg_namespace n ON n.oid = c.relnamespace
WHERE c.relname = 'tenants';
  • Columns on the table (if its a table):

SQL Query 

SELECT column_name, data_type, is_nullable, column_default
FROM information_schema.columns
WHERE table_schema = 'public' AND table_name = 'tenants'
ORDER BY ordinal_position;
  • Indexes:

SQL Query 

SELECT indexname, indexdef
FROM pg_indexes
WHERE schemaname = 'public' AND tablename = 'tenants';

2) SQL issues to fix before RLS policies work

A few schema items will error at runtime or during SELECTs:

  • UNIQUE on systems.name is global. For multi-tenant, make it per-tenant. Replace with a composite unique:
    • Drop existing unique and add unique (tenant_id, name).
  • Views that join tenants and filter systems can break under RLS if you dont add policies to read tenants.
  • Vector indexes ivfflat require ANALYZE after load and a proper extension. You created vector extension, thats good.

Apply these corrections:

SQL Query 

-- Make system name unique per tenant (NOT globally)
ALTER TABLE systems DROP CONSTRAINT IF EXISTS systems_name_key;
CREATE UNIQUE INDEX systems_unique_tenant_name ON systems(tenant_id, name);

-- If you want the old global uniqueness as well, skip this drop. Otherwise, the above is the multi-tenant friendly approach.

3) RLS policies need WITH CHECK for writes and safer USING for reads

Right now you use FOR ALL USING (...) only. For INSERT/UPDATE, you must also constrain the new row values using WITH CHECK. Also, your tenants table only allows super_admin via a custom claim, which will block joins in your views for normal users.

Safer set of policies:

SQL Query 

-- Tenants: allow authenticated users to read only their tenant row; super_admin can read/write all.
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS tenant_access ON tenants;
CREATE POLICY tenants_read_own ON tenants
  FOR SELECT TO authenticated
  USING (id = (auth.jwt()->>'tenant_id')::uuid);

CREATE POLICY tenants_admin_all ON tenants
  FOR ALL TO authenticated
  USING (auth.jwt()->>'role' = 'super_admin')
  WITH CHECK (auth.jwt()->>'role' = 'super_admin');

-- Systems
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS system_tenant_isolation ON systems;
CREATE POLICY systems_tenant_select ON systems
  FOR SELECT TO authenticated
  USING (tenant_id = (auth.jwt()->>'tenant_id')::uuid);

CREATE POLICY systems_tenant_write ON systems
  FOR INSERT TO authenticated
  WITH CHECK (tenant_id = (auth.jwt()->>'tenant_id')::uuid);

CREATE POLICY systems_tenant_update ON systems
  FOR UPDATE TO authenticated
  USING (tenant_id = (auth.jwt()->>'tenant_id')::uuid)
  WITH CHECK (tenant_id = (auth.jwt()->>'tenant_id')::uuid);

CREATE POLICY systems_tenant_delete ON systems
  FOR DELETE TO authenticated
  USING (tenant_id = (auth.jwt()->>'tenant_id')::uuid);

4) Views under RLS

Your views join against tenants and systems/executions. Under RLS, SELECT on a view applies policies of underlying tables. With the tenant read policy added above, authenticated users with tenant_id claim can now read their own tenant row, enabling the join.

If you need admin-only dashboards, consider SECURITY DEFINER helper functions or a dedicated admin role in JWT.

5) Triggers and averages

Your update_system_stats trigger queries executions on every insert. Thats fine but can be heavy. Two tweaks:

  • Use COALESCE to avoid nulls in AVG results.
  • Consider a partial index on executions(system_id) for faster aggregates if the table grows large.

Optional refinement:

SQL Query 

CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_executions_by_system_started ON executions(system_id, started_at DESC);

6) Seed + RLS order

After enabling RLS, inserts using anon role will fail. Seed with the SQL editor (superuser) or temporarily disable RLS during initial seed, or run seeds using the service role key. Since youve already inserted, youre fine, but be aware for future environments.

7) Minimal function query to test DB + RLS vs service role

  • To bypass RLS (admin fetch), use service role inside the function: 
import { createClient } from 'npm:@supabase/supabase-js@2.47.10';

const supabaseAdmin = createClient(
  Deno.env.get('SUPABASE_URL')!,
  Deno.env.get('SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY')!
);

Deno.serve(async (req) => {
  const url = new URL(req.url);
  if (req.method === 'GET' && url.pathname.endsWith('/mos-orchestrator/systems')) {
    try {
      const { data, error } = await supabaseAdmin
        .from('systems')
        .select('*')
        .limit(5);
      if (error) {
        console.error('DB error:', error);
        return new Response(JSON.stringify({ error: error.message }), { status: 400, headers: { 'content-type': 'application/json' }});
      }
      return new Response(JSON.stringify({ data }), { headers: { 'content-type': 'application/json' }});
    } catch (e) {
      console.error('Unhandled:', e);
      return new Response('Internal Server Error', { status: 500 });
    }
  }
  return new Response('Not Found', { status: 404 });
});
  • If this works, your previous 500s were likely from unhandled errors or anon-key + RLS blocks.
